## Why This Is Asked
Tests cross-store consistency, idempotency, and failure handling in a multi-datastore fraud workflow. Emphasizes concrete keys, TTLs, and read-back guarantees.

## Key Concepts
- Idempotent writes across Redis, MongoDB, Cassandra, DynamoDB
- TTL management for cache freshness
- Cross-store conflict resolution and compensating actions
- Read-path reconstruction from multiple sources

## Code Example
```javascript
async function placeFraudAlert(reqId, payload){
  // Redis: cache with short TTL
  await redis.set(`alert:${reqId}`, JSON.stringify(payload), 'EX', 3600);

  // MongoDB: embed alert reference in customer profile
  await mongo.updateOne({customerId: payload.customerId},
    { $push: { alerts: { id: reqId, ...payload } } }, { upsert: true });

  // Cassandra: append per-customer transaction event
  await cassandra.execute(`INSERT INTO alerts_by_customer (customer_id, ts, req_id, details) VALUES (?, toTimeuuid(now()), ?, ?)`,
    [payload.customerId, reqId, payload]);

  // DynamoDB: immutable audit log
  await dynamo.putItem({
    TableName: 'Audit',
    Item: { PK: { S: `ALERT#${reqId}` },
            ...payloadToDynamoItem(payload) }
  });
}
```

